A translation surface is a topological surface equipped with an atlas of charts to the plane where the transition functions are translations.

text.tspan: The set of all translation surfaces:

g.ns0:text: Surfaces in the set of all\\\\\ntranslation surfaces $\\sM$\\ldots

Immersions place a partial order on the space $\tM$ of all simply connected translation surfaces.

{\bf Theorem.} The set $\tM \cup \{0\}$, where $0$ denotes the degenerate, single point ``translation surface''
is a \\
complete lattice, i.e., each subset of $\tM \cup \{0\}$ has a supremum and an infimum
in $\tM \cup \{0\}$.
Convergence in $\\tM$
Let $\\tilde S_n$ be a sequence in $\\tM$. Then $\\tilde S_n$ converges to $\\tilde S$ \nif and only if both of the following hold:

For $n \geq 1$, let $R_n \subset \C$ be the $n$-th roots of unity. Let 
$S_n=\C \sm R_n$ with basepoint at the origin.

Then, the sequence of universal covers $\tilde S_n$ converges
to the unit disk.

text.tspan: The topology on the disk bundle:

g.ns0:text: The disk bundle over $\\tM$ is $$\\tE=\\{(\\tilde S, p):p \\in \\tilde S \\in \\tM\\}.$$

text.tspan: Topologizing the space of all surfaces:

g.ns0:text:
Let $S_n \in \sM$ be a sequence of translation surfaces, and let $S \in \sM$ be a potential limit.
Let $s_n$ and $s$ be their basepoints and let $\tilde S_n$ and $\tilde S$ be their universal covers. 

Then, $S_n$ {\em converges} to $S$ in $\sM$ if

\begin{cenumerate}
\item[A'.] If $K$ is a compact disk in $\tilde S$, then $\exists \iota_n: K \imm S_n$ for $n$ sufficiently large.
\item[B'.] If $\tilde p \in K^\circ \subset \tilde S$ is a lift of $s \in S$, then there is a sequence $\tilde p_n \in K$ tending to $\tilde p$ so 
that $\iota_{n}(\tilde p_n)$ is a lift of $s_n \in S_n$ for $n$ sufficiently large.
\item[A''.] For each $\tilde U \in \tM$, if $\exists j_n:\tilde U \imm S_n$ for infinitely many $n$, then $\exists j:\tilde U \imm S$.
\item[B''.] If $j_n(\tilde u_n)$ is a lift of $s_n \in S_n$ and $\tilde u_n \to \tilde u$ in $\tilde U$, then $j(\tilde u)$ is a lift $s \in S$. 
\end{cenumerate}

\begin{cenumerate}
\item[A'.] If $K$ is a compact disk in $\tilde S$, then $\exists \iota_n: K \imm S_n$ for $n$ sufficiently large.
\item[A''.] For each $\tilde U \in \tM$, if $\exists j_n:\tilde U \imm S_n$ for infinitely many $n$, then $\exists j:\tilde U \imm S$.
\item[B.] a point $\tilde p \in \tilde S$ is a lift of $s \in S$ if and only if
there is a sequence $\tilde p_n \in \tilde S_n$ so that $(\tilde S_n, \tilde p_n)$
converges to $(\tilde S,\tilde p)$ in $\tE$. 
\end{cenumerate}
We also topologize $\\sE$, the surface bundle over $\\sM$\\ldots

{\bf Theorem.} The topologies on $\tM$, $\tE$, $\sM$, and $\sE$
are second countable and Hausdorff.

{\bf Compactness Theorem.} For any $\epsilon>0$, the set of surfaces in $\sM$ or $\tM$ for which 
the basepoint has an open $\epsilon$-neighborhood isometric to the open
$\epsilon$-ball in the plane is compact.

Let $S$ be a translation surface, \\\\\nand let $u$ be a unit complex \\\\\nnumber. The {\\em straight-line \\\\\nflow} is given in local \\\\\ncoordinates by $F^t(z)=z+tu$,\\\\\nwith $t \\in \\R$.\n\n
$\\GL(2,\\R)$ acts on translation surfaces. \\\\\nIf $A \\in \\GL(2,\\R)$, then we obtain \\\\\n$A(S)$ by post-composing all charts\\\\\nfrom $S$ to the plane with $A$.
Let $A^t(x+iy)=e^t x+i e^{-t} y$. The {\\em Teichm\\"uller geodesic flow} on \n$\\sM$ or $\\sE$ is the affine action of $A^t$ on these spaces.
The {\\em vertical straight-line flow} is locally $F^t(z)=z+it$.\n

Two pointed translation surfaces, $S_1$ and $S_2$, are \\\\\n{\\em translation equivalent (equal)}\nif there is a \\\\\nhomeomorphism $h:S_1 \\to S_2$ which respects the basepoints\nand is a translation in local coordinates.
{\\bf Def.} An {\\em embedding} is a one-to-one immersion. We denote embeddings by $D \\emb S$.
{\\bf Thm.} If $S_n \\to S_\\infty$ and $K \\subset S_\\infty$ is a compact disk,\nthen $K \\emb S_n$ for $n$ sufficently large.

{\bf Theorem
(in the spirit of Masur's Criterion).} \\
Suppose $S$ is a translation surface of area one. If there is a sequence of times $t_n \to \infty$
and a sequence of basepoints $s_n$ of $S$ so that under the Teichm\"uller flow
$A^{t_n}(S,s_n)$ converges to a unit area surface in $\sM$, then the vertical
straight line flow is uniquely ergodic.

{\bf Theorem.}
Suppose $S$ is a translation surface of area one. If there is a sequence of times $t_n \to \infty$
so that under the Teichm\"uller flow
$A^{t_n}(S)$ converges to a unit area surface $S_\infty \in \sM$, then the vertical
straight line flow, $F^t:S \to S$, is uniquely ergodic.
The individual ergodic theorem says that for any \\\\\nintegrable $f$, there is a set $B=B(f) \\subset S$ of full measure so that the averages\n
$$\\text{avg}_+(x)=\\int_0^T f \\circ F^t(x)~dt \\quad \\text{and} \\quad \\text{avg}_-(x)=\\int_{-T}^0 f \\circ F^t(x)~dt$$
exist and are equal.
Now choose $K$ to be a compact disk in $S_\\infty$ with \n$$\\lambda_\\infty(K)>\\text{max}\\big(1-\\lambda(B_\\pm)\\big).$$
Since $A^{t_n}(S) \\to S_\\infty$, there are embeddings\\\\\n$\\epsilon_n:K \\emb A^{t_n}(S)$ for $n$ sufficiently large.

Let $L=\limsup A^{-t_n} \circ \epsilon_n(K) \subset S$. \\
Then $\lambda(L) \geq \lambda_\infty(K)$, so there is a $b_- \in L \cap B_-$.
So, up to passing to a subsequence, we can assume that 
$$A^{t_n}(S, b_-) \to (S_\infty, c_-)$$
for some $c_- \in K \subset S_\infty$.

Again, let $L\'=\\limsup A^{-t_n} \\circ \\epsilon_n(K) \\subset S$. \\\\\nThere is a $b_+ \\in L\' \\cap B_+$, and up to subsequence\n$$A^{t_n}(S, b_-,b_+) \\to (S_\\infty, c_-, c_+)$$\nfor some $c_-,c_+ \\in K \\subset S_\\infty$.
